{"warnings":{"parse":{"*":"The value passed for \"page\" contains invalid or non-normalized data. Textual data should be valid, NFC-normalized Unicode without C0 control characters other than HT (\\t), LF (\\n), and CR (\\r)."}},"parse":{"title":"Terribilit\u00e0","pageid":48323509,"revid":843559407,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg/220px-%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"330\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg/330px-%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg/440px-%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3400\" data-file-height=\"5100\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:%27Moses%27_by_Michelangelo_JBU310.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>\"<a href=\"/wiki/Moses_(Michelangelo)\" title=\"Moses (Michelangelo)\">Moses</a>\" by Michelangelo</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Terribilit\u00e0</b>, the spelling in modern Italian, or <b>terribilt\u00e0</b>, as <a href=\"/wiki/Michelangelo\" title=\"Michelangelo\">Michelangelo</a>'s 16th century contemporaries tended to spell it, is a quality of provoking  terror (the literal meaning), awe, or a sense of the sublime, in the viewer, that is ascribed to his art.  It is perhaps especially applied to his <a href=\"/wiki/Sculpture\" title=\"Sculpture\">sculptures</a>, such as his figures of <a href=\"/wiki/David_(Michelangelo)\" title=\"David (Michelangelo)\"><i>David</i></a> or in <a href=\"/wiki/Moses_(Michelangelo)\" title=\"Moses (Michelangelo)\"><i>Moses</i></a>.\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Pope_Julius_II\" title=\"Pope Julius II\">Pope Julius II</a> was apparently the first to describe Michelangelo as a <i>uomo terribile</i> (\"terror-inducing man\"), apparently describing his difficult character as much as his art. This <i>terribilit\u00e0</i>, also references the <a href=\"/wiki/Neoplatonism\" title=\"Neoplatonism\">neoplatonics</a> of humanists such as <a href=\"/wiki/Marsilio_Ficino\" title=\"Marsilio Ficino\">Marsilio Ficino</a>, who had known Michelangelo in his youth.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Michelangelo's friend and collaborator <a href=\"/wiki/Sebastiano_del_Piombo\" title=\"Sebastiano del Piombo\">Sebastiano del Piombo</a> reported in a letter to him of 15 October 1520 on a private audience with <a href=\"/wiki/Pope_Leo_X\" title=\"Pope Leo X\">Pope Leo X</a>.  After praising Michelangelo's work, the pope continued \"But he is <i>terribile</i>, as you see; one cannot deal with him\".  Sebastiano responded \"that your <i>terribile</i> character did not harm anyone, and that you appear <i>terribile</i> for love of the great works you carry out.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Terribilit%C3%A0&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Lle\u00f3 Ca\u00f1al, Vicente, Revista de Libros:Tintoretto 2, 2 Abril 2007, p.2</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Exhibition handlist for \"Michelangelo &amp; Sebastiano\", 2017, National Gallery. Catalogue # 33, from <a href=\"/wiki/Casa_Buonarroti\" title=\"Casa Buonarroti\">Casa Buonarroti</a>, Florence.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bibliography\">Bibliography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Terribilit%C3%A0&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Bibliography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Hodson, Rupert (2000). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=-BszAAAACAAJ\"><i>Miguel \u00c1ngel, escultor</i></a>. Brand. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-84-95481-02-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-84-95481-02-3\">978-84-95481-02-3</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Miguel+%C3%81ngel%2C+escultor&amp;rft.pub=Brand&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft.isbn=978-84-95481-02-3&amp;rft.aulast=Hodson&amp;rft.aufirst=Rupert&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-BszAAAACAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATerribilit%C3%A0\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Mart\u00edn Gonz\u00e1lez, Juan Jos\u00e9 (1974). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=NcI2AQAAIAAJ\"><i>Juan de Juni: vida y obra</i></a>. Direcci\u00f3n General de Bellas Artes, Ministerio de Educac\u00edon y Ciencia, &#91;Patronato Nacional de Museos. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standa